1️⃣ Data Ingestion Layer ⚙️

This layer is responsible for collecting data from source systems and bringing it into the data platform. Data ingestion can occur in batch mode or streaming mode.

📌 Examples:

Tools like Apache Kafka, Amazon Kinesis, and Google Cloud DataFlow are used to fetch and transfer large volumes of data.

2️⃣ Data Storage and Integration Layer 🛠️

This layer stores ingested data and integrates it for further processing. It can leverage both relational databases (such as IBM DB2, Oracle DB) and NoSQL databases (like MongoDB, Cassandra).

📌 Examples:

Amazon RDS and Google Cloud SQL for relational databases.

IBM Cloudant for NoSQL solutions.

3️⃣ Data Processing Layer 🔧

This layer is responsible for processing and transforming data through validation, cleansing, and applying business logic.

📌 Examples:

Apache Spark processes large datasets in real-time or batch mode using languages like Python, Java, and R.

🔄 Transformations in this Layer:

Structuring – Altering formats and schemas.

Normalization – Cleaning data to reduce redundancy.

Denormalization – Combining data from different tables for more efficient queries.

Data Cleaning – Fixing inconsistencies to ensure reliable data.

4️⃣ Analysis and User Interface Layer 📊

In this layer, processed data is delivered to users through dashboards and interactive reports. Business stakeholders can analyze and visualize the data.

📌 Examples:

Tools like Tableau, Microsoft Power BI, and Jupyter Notebooks create visual representations and data analyses.

5️⃣ Data Pipeline Layer 🚇

This layer overlays multiple other layers to build and maintain continuous data pipelines that manage data ingestion, storage, and processing.

📌 Examples:

Tools such as Apache Airflow and Google DataFlow.

